{
  "texts": [
    "We might be concerned about the validity of a UK pre-election AI poll, for instance, if we discovered that a model for predicting the probability of voting for the Labour party gave more importance to seemingly spurious correlates such as shopping habits or personality traits over well established predictors such as class, age, education, area-level contextual information, etc.",
    "We do not advocate for a specific measure of importance-though we do emphasise these measures should be interpretable and comparable across models, samples and pollsters.",
    "An example of such a measure is permutation importance (Altmann et al. 2010).",
    "A key feature of AI polling is that a prediction is made for a number of 'cells' or voter-types.",
    "A challenge is that every pollster can in principle define cells differently-e.g., each pollster may choose to operationalise age using different brackets, or to break down cells by interest in politics and past-vote, while others might choose not to."
  ]
}